           =20
            <h2>Electrical Engineering Conversions</h2>
            <p>Electrical engineers work with power, energy, voltage, curre=
nt, and resistance measurements that occasionally require unit conversions,=
 particularly when dealing with international equipment specifications or c=
omparing different power rating systems. While electrical units are general=
ly standardized internationally through SI units, practical applications of=
ten involve conversions between different scales or related quantities.</p>
           =20
            <div class=3D"info-box">
                <strong>Power System Note:</strong> Electrical power can be=
 expressed in watts, kilowatts, megawatts, or horsepower depending on appli=
cation. Understanding these conversions helps in equipment selection, capac=
ity planning, and energy consumption analysis. One horsepower equals approx=
imately 746 watts or 0.746 kilowatts.
            </div>
           =20
            <h2>Hydraulic and Pneumatic System Conversions</h2>
            <p>Hydraulic and pneumatic systems in mechanical and industrial=
 engineering require careful attention to pressure, flow rate, and force co=
nversions. These systems often use specialized units like bar, psi, GPM (ga=
llons per minute), and CFM (cubic feet per minute) that engineers must conv=
ert between for proper system design and component selection.</p>
           =20
            <p>Hydraulic pressure ratings, cylinder forces, and fluid flow =
rates must be precisely specified to ensure system performance and safety. =
A hydraulic cylinder rated at 3000 psi operates at approximately 207 bar or=
 20.7 MPa. Understanding these equivalencies allows engineers to select app=
ropriate components from manufacturers worldwide and ensures compatibility =
across different system specifications.</p>
           =20
            <h2>Material Properties and Specifications</h2>
            <p>Material specifications often appear in different unit syste=
ms depending on the standard or manufacturer origin. Steel strength grades,=
 concrete compressive strength, timber stress grades, and other material pr=
operties require conversion for proper specification and verification. Engi=
neers must ensure that materials meet project requirements regardless of ho=
w properties are originally stated.</p>
           =20
            <div class=3D"table-container">
                <table>
